commit.message:
last weekday of month

the '~' means different things in OpenBSD and systemd.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cron#Non-standard_characters

https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd.time.html#:~:text=last%20Monday

also obey "CRON_MAIL_FORMAT=nometadata" from drop-in configs snippets

$ cat /etc/systemd/system/cron-monthly-check-dfsg-status.service.d/override.conf
[Service]
Environment=CRON_MAIL_FORMAT=nometadata

---------------------

with "OnSuccess=cron-mail@%n:Success:nometadata.service"
we get _2_ mails: 1 ok from new OnSuccess
& 1 nok from existing OnSuccess that can't be disabled

I would propose this
/usr/lib/systemd/system/cron-monthly-check-dfsg-status.service.d/systemd-cron.conf
to check-dfsg-status maintainers.

Replace openssl (-lcrypto) with libmd (-lmd)

We only use it for MD5 calculation, so the huge libssl dep is kinda
wasted. libmd is already used by dpkg &a. so it's not an additional
dependency. Also, going from
  $ ldd out/build/bin/systemd-crontab-generator
          linux-vdso.so.1 (0x00007fff1a9f0000)
          libcrypto.so.3 => /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libcrypto.so.3 (0x00007ff13e4d1000)
          libstdc++.so.6 => /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libstdc++.so.6 (0x00007ff13e2b7000)
          libm.so.6 => /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libm.so.6 (0x00007ff13e1d8000)
          libgcc_s.so.1 => /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libgcc_s.so.1 (0x00007ff13e1b8000)
          libc.so.6 => /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libc.so.6 (0x00007ff13dfd7000)
          /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2 (0x00007ff13e987000)
to
  $ ldd out/build/bin/systemd-crontab-generator
          linux-vdso.so.1 (0x00007ffcf714f000)
          libmd.so.0 => /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libmd.so.0 (0x00007f4e44226000)
          libstdc++.so.6 => /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libstdc++.so.6 (0x00007f4e4400c000)
          libm.so.6 => /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libm.so.6 (0x00007f4e43f2d000)
          libgcc_s.so.1 => /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libgcc_s.so.1 (0x00007f4e43f0d000)
          libc.so.6 => /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libc.so.6 (0x00007f4e43d2c000)
          /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2 (0x00007f4e44267000)
means we also go from
  -rw-r--r-- 1 root root 4.5M 10-23 19:52 /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libcrypto.so.3
to
  -rw-r--r-- 1 root root  47K 2022-07-10  /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libmd.so.0
which means our RSS and pagefaults go down by half
(according to /bin/time), and we save 1-2ms/run (according to bash time).

The libmd interface is also simpler and infallible, unlike the
openssl interface (and we were using the "deprecated" EVP_md5() API),
and we can use its own binary-string formatter instead of rolling our own.

I had wanted to use libmd originally but couldn't drive it correctly for
some reason (probably because of the confusingly-named functions).

commit.message:
Silence -Wunused-result for pipe2()

Borderline impossible to actually happen, but
  g++ -g -O2 -ffile-prefix-map=/<BUILDDPREFIXDIR>/systemd-cron-2.3.0=. -fstack-protector-strong -Wformat -Werror=format-security -Wall -Wextra -fno-exceptions -Wno-psabi -Wdate-time -D_FORTIFY_SOURCE=2 -std=c++20 -I /<BUILDDPREFIXDIR>/systemd-cron-2.3.0/out/build/include  /<BUILDDPREFIXDIR>/systemd-cron-2.3.0/src/bin/systemd-crontab-generator.cpp -o /<BUILDDPREFIXDIR>/systemd-cron-2.3.0/out/build/bin/systemd-crontab-generator -Wl,-z,relro -Wl,-z,now -lcrypto
  /<BUILDDPREFIXDIR>/systemd-cron-2.3.0/src/bin/crontab.cpp: In function ‘int list(const char*, const char*)’:
  /<BUILDDPREFIXDIR>/systemd-cron-2.3.0/src/bin/crontab.cpp:231:22: warning: ignoring return value of ‘int pipe2(int*, int)’ declared with attribute ‘warn_unused_result’ [-Wunused-result]
    231 |                 pipe2(pipe, O_CLOEXEC);
        |                 ~~~~~^~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
